Date:7/18/2012 9:09:58 AM
From:Chid
I could get this horribly wrong but let me give this a shot...
First let's arrive what a new owner might do:
Since Coke is already a cash generating machine it probably does not need the
cash on its books. Assume it needs 0.
Second, though the affiliates have synergies we can assume that they are
extraneous to the actual operations of Coke.
Assuming affiliates are sold and all the cash is used to pay off the debt and
reduce shareholder equity we can arrive at a new Shareholder equity of 2326.

Shareholder Equity 3345
Debt 2124
-Cash -1231
-Affiliates -1912
Final Shareholder Equity 2326
No debt

Note that the company earned operating income 1598 (excl equity and interest
income), using a tax rate of 35% and depreciation of 167, and actual capital
expenditure of 387 we can arrive at net owner earnings to assets of 819. That
would be a ROE of 35%. This is a very high unleveraged ROE number.

If I were to assume the new owner can earn 23% on Coke conservatively we can
arrive at the following analysis....
Assuming 355mil shares, the BVPS of 6.55.
If you apply CAGR of 23% for the BV for 10 years you will arrive at a BV of
51.9 at the end of 1998.
Assuming Coke still earns 23% it would earn 11.94 that year and if you apply a
15x multiplier you can see how Coke could be worth 179. (Buffett bot the shares
at avg price of 43.85 giving the magic CAGR of 15% which is the Buffett min
requirement for investments).

Obviously the 23% is the big if but without historical information on how much
Investments were in affiliates historically this will always be a question
mark. Does anyone have this data or know how to obtain it?

Add debt to this and you could juice the returns some more I guess.

