%BOM---------------------
Date:7/24/2012 3:55:33 PM
From:Spekulatius
re PBR - i am not interested in PBR at this time. The reason is simple, they
are sitting on a lot of oil, but it's going to be expensive to get it out. Some
estimate 20$/brl exploration and development cost and then one needs to add
some lifting costs and taxes etc. They need to borrow money to do it.

There are quite a few oil stocks out there, that have proved reserves in the
ground valued at less than 15$/brl. Examples are HES, TOT and E. TOT and E pay
an even richer dividend than PBR and I do not see the risk that i see with PBR.
For me at least, buying proved reserves at 15$/brl (or less) is better than
buying unproved reserves that cost more than 20$/brl (my assumption, correct me
if I am wrong) and that is why I am not interested in PBR.

i do want to point out that E and TOT are located in Europe but i do not think
it matters much. Their reserves are all over in the world, so they are only
affected by the Euro mess with their local operations (refinery, chemistry ops
etc.) Those only constitute probably less than 25% of their NAV and earnings,
so the impact on the Euro issues is that not that;. And if the crude price
falls because of the Euro issues, it will affect every integrated oil company
(including PBR), not just the European ones.
